TY  - JOUR
T1  - Integrated Manufacturing and Job Design: Moderating Effects of Organizational Inertia
AU  - Dean, James W.
AU  - Snell, Scott A.
Y1  - 1991/12/01
PY  - 1991
DA  - 1991/12/01
N1  - doi: 10.5465/256389
DO  - 10.5465/256389
T2  - Academy of Management Journal
JF  - Academy of Management Journal
JO  - AMJ
SP  - 776
EP  - 804
VL  - 34
IS  - 4
PB  - Academy of Management
N2  - This study investigated the relationship between integrated manufacturing, a new manufacturing paradigm comprising advanced technology, just-in-time inventory control, and total quality management, and job characteristics (task uncertainty and interdependence). We hypothesized that performance, size, and external control would moderate this relationship. Data from plant and functional managers and nonmanagerial employees in 123 companies showed no main effects of integrated manufacturing on job design among employees in operations, quality control and assurance, and production control. Rather, the relationships were contingent on organizational context. We discuss organizational inertia and resource availability as alternative theoretical perspectives on the impact of organizational context.
AB  - This study investigated the relationship between integrated manufacturing, a new manufacturing paradigm comprising advanced technology, just-in-time inventory control, and total quality management, and job characteristics (task uncertainty and interdependence). We hypothesized that performance, size, and external control would moderate this relationship. Data from plant and functional managers and nonmanagerial employees in 123 companies showed no main effects of integrated manufacturing on job design among employees in operations, quality control and assurance, and production control. Rather, the relationships were contingent on organizational context. We discuss organizational inertia and resource availability as alternative theoretical perspectives on the impact of organizational context.
